The royalty, corporate taxes and financial contribution by Shell companies to the Nigerian government in the last five years have hit N4.62 trillion ($17.8 billion). Country Chair, Shell companies in Nigeria, Mr. Osagie Okunbor, who declared this during the formal launch of Shell 2018 briefing note in Lagos, yesterday, disclosed that the company paid $1.7 billion (N515.14 billion) in corporate taxes and royalty to the government in 2018 alone. Okunbor, who was accompanied to the event by Managing Director, Shell Nigeria Exploration and Production Company (SNEPCo), Mr. Bayo Ojulari, and his counterpart at Shell Nigeria Gas (SNG), Mr. Ed Ubong, said between 2014 and 2018, Shell companies in Nigeria made $17.8 billion (N4.62 trillion) economic contribution such as taxes, royalties and levies from SPDC JV parties to the Nigerian government. “$2 billion (N375.16 billion) was contributed from SPDC JV parties, SNEPCo and its co-ventures to the Niger Delta Development Commission (NDDC) since inception in 2002,” Ojulari added. Giving a breakdown of 2018 economic contribution to Nigeria by Shell, Okunbor said: “The Shell Petroleum Development Company (SPDC) alone paid $0.9 billion (N272.72 billion) to the Nigerian government in 2018, while the contribution by SNEPCo in terms of royalty and corporate taxes was $0.8 billion (N242.42 billion).” He said 92 per cent of the entire contracts awarded by Shell in Nigeria in 2018 were awarded to Nigerian companies. “Shell companies in Nigeria spent $1.3 billion on contracts awarded to these Nigerian companies,” he said. Stating that 96 per cent employees of Shell in the country are Nigerians, the company said its Joint Venture contributed $2 billion to the NDDC/Shell share of $49.5 million (N14.99 billion). “$56.2 million (N17.03 billion) was contributed by SPDC JV, SNEPCo, Shell Nigeria Gas and All Ondirect spending on social investment projects (Shell share $31 million; N9.39 billion). “617,000 barrels of oil equivalent per day average daily production by Shell-operated ventures in Nigeria in 2018. “$239 million (N44.36 billion) was committed to social investment funds disbursed for communitydriven projects between 2013 and 2018 (Shell share $16 million – N3.88 billion),” Shell added. Specifically, out of 617,000 barrels of oil equivalent per day average production by Shell-operated ventures in Nigeria in 2018, 461,000 barrels of oil equivalent per day, Okunbor said, came from SPDC JV and 156,000 barrels per day from SNEPCo production sharing contract (PSC). On gas, the briefing note read, SPDC JV and SNEPCo are major gas suppliers to the Nigeria Liquified Natural Gas (NLNG) plant from their onshore and offshore fields. “In 2018, NLNG paid approximately $398 million (N120.61 billion) in income tax to the Federal Government. “13 per cent of gridconnected electricity was supplied by SPDC JV Afam IV power plant in 2018,” the briefing note read.